<subSubSection id="59F4654C56086944C88C01E0861AFF75" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="68" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="115136C756086944C88C01E0861AFF75" blockId="7.[151,1437,1788,2031]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="68" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BC88C01E08203F89A" bold="true" box="[151,276,1788,1814]" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BC90101E08119F89A" authority="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti, 2022" authorityName="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2022" box="[282,526,1788,1814]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinaejuxta" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BC90101E08119F89A" box="[282,526,1788,1814]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">Teliphasa spinaejuxta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCA0E01E18179F89B" bold="true" box="[533,622,1789,1815]" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="38A957AE5608694BCA0E01E18179F89B" box="[533,622,1789,1815]" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is distinct from all other 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BCB9301E0875BF89A" box="[904,1100,1788,1814]" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCB9301E080E3F89A" box="[904,1012,1788,1814]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">Teliphasa</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by male genital with the apex of the large, plate-like juxta bearing two strong spines. Externally, 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BCB95003D873BF8B6" authority="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti, 2022" authorityName="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2022" box="[910,1068,1825,1850]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinaejuxta" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCB95003D873BF8B6" box="[910,1068,1825,1850]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">T. spinaejuxta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCC2F003D8798F8B7" bold="true" box="[1076,1167,1825,1851]" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="38A957AE5608694BCC2F003D8798F8B7" box="[1076,1167,1825,1851]" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="89D52A425608694BCCBB003C8613F8B7" box="[1184,1284,1824,1851]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1198,1222]" captionTargetBox="[168,1413,193,1164]" captionTargetId="figure-29@3.[151,1435,181,1175]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 7, male &amp; 8, female, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov; 9, male, T. erythrina; 10, male, T. similalbifusa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577736" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577736/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">Figs 7, 8</figureCitation>
) is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BC88C0059821EF8D2" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[151,265,1860,1886]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BC88C0059821EF8D2" box="[151,265,1860,1886]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">T. elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B365608694BC903005882D4F8D2" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[280,451,1860,1887]" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">
Liu 
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BC9530059826EF8D2" box="[328,377,1860,1886]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="89D52A425608694BC9D50058810AF8D3" box="[462,541,1860,1887]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1347,1371]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,193,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-29@5.[159,1428,181,1323]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Female genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 11, T. nubilosa; 12, T. hamata; 13, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577738" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577738/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BCA45005981C4F8D2" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1896" box="[606,723,1860,1886]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Macalla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albifusa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCA45005981C4F8D2" box="[606,723,1860,1886]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">T. albifusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B365608694BCAF800588099F8D2" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[739,910,1860,1887]" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">
Liu 
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCB0800598053F8D2" box="[787,836,1860,1886]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="89D52A425608694BCB81005880FCF8D3" box="[922,1003,1860,1887]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1198,1222]" captionTargetBox="[168,1413,193,1164]" captionTargetId="figure-29@3.[151,1435,181,1175]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 7, male &amp; 8, female, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov; 9, male, T. erythrina; 10, male, T. similalbifusa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577736" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577736/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
), but is distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BCCC500598647F8D2" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[1246,1360,1860,1886]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCCC500598647F8D2" box="[1246,1360,1860,1886]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">T. elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the fuscous forewing with whitish scales on medial area and a fuscous band in the basal area (whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BCD3800758681F80E" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[1315,1430,1896,1922]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCD3800758681F80E" box="[1315,1430,1896,1922]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">T. elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the forewing is almost uniformly fuscous), and from 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BCAE700918064F82A" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1896" box="[764,883,1932,1958]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Macalla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albifusa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCAE700918064F82A" box="[764,883,1932,1958]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">T. albifusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the medial whitish area of forewing densely tinged with fuscous, and by the presence of a bar-shaped discal spot (whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BCC3F00AD878DF846" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1896" box="[1060,1178,1968,1994]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Macalla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albifusa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCC3F00AD878DF846" box="[1060,1178,1968,1994]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">T. albifusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the medial area of the forewing is whitish with two prominent fuscous spots (
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B365608694BCB1C00C880A3F862" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[775,948,2004,2031]" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">
Liu 
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCB2C00C9807EF862" box="[823,873,2004,2030]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="89D52A425608694BCBDB00C88705F863" box="[960,1042,2004,2031]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1198,1222]" captionTargetBox="[168,1413,193,1164]" captionTargetId="figure-29@3.[151,1435,181,1175]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 7, male &amp; 8, female, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov; 9, male, T. erythrina; 10, male, T. similalbifusa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577736" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577736/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
)). In male genitalia, 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D445608694BCCE400C9868BF862" authority="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti, 2022" authorityName="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2022" box="[1279,1436,2005,2030]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinaejuxta" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="239AEAD55608694BCCE400C9868BF862" box="[1279,1436,2005,2030]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="67">T. spinaejuxta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="239AEAD556076944C88C078B83E5FF3D" bold="true" box="[151,242,151,177]" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="38A957AE56076944C88C078B83E5FF3D" box="[151,242,151,177]" pageId="8" pageNumber="68" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="89D52A4256076944C918078B8243FF3D" box="[259,340,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1315,198,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[247,1340,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Male genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 14, T. erythrina; 15, T. nubilosa; 16, T. dodaki sp. nov.; 17, T. similalbifusa; 18, T. hamata; 19, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577740" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577740/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) differs from 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D4456076944C9E8078B8172FF3D" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[499,613,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis id="239AEAD556076944C9E8078B8172FF3D" box="[499,613,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">T. elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the juxta with its two short, apical spike-like processes (juxta without processes in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D4456076944C93307A7828CFF59" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[296,411,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis id="239AEAD556076944C93307A7828CFF59" box="[296,411,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">T. elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In comparison to the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D4456076944CB7707A780F5FF59" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1896" box="[876,994,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Macalla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albifusa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD556076944CB7707A780F5FF59" box="[876,994,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">T. albifusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the costa of the valva is narrower and almost straight in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D4456076944C97A07C382EAFF74" authority="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti, 2022" authorityName="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2022" box="[353,509,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinaejuxta" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="239AEAD556076944C97A07C382EAFF74" box="[353,509,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">T. spinaejuxta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="239AEAD556076944CA1F07C38149FF75" bold="true" box="[516,606,223,249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="38A957AE56076944CA1F07C38149FF75" box="[516,606,223,249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="68" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D4456076944CAFF07C3804DFF75" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1896" box="[740,858,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Macalla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albifusa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD556076944CAFF07C3804DFF75" box="[740,858,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">T. albifusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is convex (
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B3656076944CBE307C387B5FF75" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[1016,1186,223,249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="68" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">
Liu 
<emphasis id="239AEAD556076944CC3C07C3874FFF75" box="[1063,1112,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="89D52A4256076944CCB607C387E8FF75" box="[1197,1279,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1315,198,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[247,1340,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Male genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 14, T. erythrina; 15, T. nubilosa; 16, T. dodaki sp. nov.; 17, T. similalbifusa; 18, T. hamata; 19, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577740" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577740/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="59F4654C56076944C8DC061E814FFDED" pageId="8" pageNumber="68" type="description">
<paragraph id="115136C756076944C8DC061E80BCFE21" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis id="239AEAD556076944C8DC061E824CFE90" bold="true" box="[199,347,258,284]" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">Description:</emphasis>
Adult with labial palpi upturned. Thorax covered with fuscous scales. Forewing with basal area olivaceous, outlined with fuscous. Medial whitish area tinged with olive scales. Postmedial fuscous zigzag line running outwards to vein R 
<subScript id="8D6A348256076944C9B9064182BDFEE7" attach="left" box="[418,426,349,363]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">5</subScript>
, then inwards, running parallel to median venation, then obliquely running to centre of the hind margin. Postmedial area shiny fuscous. Hindwing postmedial area fuscous, paler towards base. Legs fuscous and banded with white scales. Abdomen banded with black and white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="115136C756076944C8DC06AB80E7FD95" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">Male genitalia with uncus subovate, tegumen-vinculum complex forming an oval, saccus elongated; juxta broad, rectangular with a pair of apical spines; transtilla membranous; valva almost rounded, median (inner) surface densely covered with long setae; distal half of aedeagus strongly sclerotised.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="115136C756076944C8DC053F814FFDED" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="68">Female genitalia posterior and anterior apophyses of equal length; ductus bursae slightly bent; corpus bursae oval with a patch of cornuti towards tip.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
